host_about:
My name is Fabio and I along with my friend and colleague Willian will ensure to provide you a wonderful stay in our apartments across London.

Willian, Throughout his extensive travels, his unusual name – a derivative of William – has led to much curiosity. An Ecuadorian by birth, He has added to my higher education internationally, with economic studies in the USA, language training in Japan, and a BA and MBA in the United Kingdom.

I am a 37 year old professional, currently working and living in London, Willian is 30 year old professional, currently working and living in lively London. the most exciting and bigger property market in the world. During all this description of myself well mostly Willian, you will find out how travelling could probably be Willian's and I number 1 hobbie. Although, We do not see it as a hobby but a luxury :). We do also enjoy playing sports, attending concerts, going to the movies, clubbing, hanging out, cooking and much more! 

Airbnb is awesome. Willian remembers his first time using the portal was back in 2010, when he travelled to Tokyo to attend an university interview over there. He had booked an comfortable duplex apartment in Shinjuku from this lovely Japanese guy, Junichi. He was amazed to see the true meaning of hospitality, being a host is more than just being the doorman or the typical receptionist at concierge, it is being someone who receives, treat and entertains other people as guests. 

All my life Willian and I have dedicated quite a lot of time to travel around the globe where We have had the opportunity to meet amazing people and experienced other cultures, costumes, and more. That is exactly why I am currently working in the hospitality industry with my colleague and friend Fabio because what I have learned all these years travelling around is that hospitality is the friendly and generous reception and entertainment of guests, visitors, or strangers not matter where people come from.

Fabio and I look forward welcoming and hosting some many guest in the upcoming years. I will truly give you my 100% to ensure your stay goes very well why you are staying at my apartments. I hope you enjoy the experience and adventure and thank you in advance :).

Your hosts,
Willian - Fabio

notes: The studio-apartment is part of a three-storey house but you will have your own separate entrance door to access the independent studio-apartment.

High frequency: at least six buses per hour, even on Sunday and holidays; from 5 a.m. to 12 p.m. 11-minute walk to a large supermarket. For those who are traveling by car: free parking at your disposal. Gas station within 2-minute drive.
access: You can take bus n° 9 (from main train station) or bus n° 1 to come to the studio-apartment. A three-minute walk will bring you to the studio-apartment. Refer also to the map that we send separately.  If you come by car you can park it in front of the studio-apartment.
interaction: Before arrival: we will send you a PDF-file with a map to the studio-apartment. We remain available per phone or e-mail for any information until you arrive. name: Zen Permaculture Harry Potter Room
summary: A tucked-away room in this vast wonderland house, good for people who are up to magical things. Chickens, edible forest garden and outdoor eating spots, delightful housemates.  10 minutes by bus to Central Station.
space: Its a tiny sweet room in a spacious, gracious house. It is furnished with a single bed, wardrobe and drawers, a bedside table, and a study desk & chair if you want one.    Its a creative fun household, with chickens to give you breakfast, a cat to snuggle, all surrounded by a forest of green.     All this peacefulness is just 10 minutes to Sydney Central Station. Long stays are possible, but we must get to know each other through a one-week booking first, to make sure we are both happy.   Our house is semi-Japanese. That means, we aspire to be super-observant, doing the small things that matter. Like keeping your room crisp and restful, and making you happy. I usually have live-in assistants who help keep the place nice, and you looked after. We often do easy yoga in the evenings, and you will be invited to join in. There is no T.V. here, that helps keep the place peaceful, and the human connections rich and lively.

notes: I aim to make this house Five-Star value. Its not the size of the room, or private bathroom, but its the people that you will get a chance to meet and interact with.  If you look at the profiles of my past guests, you will notice they are all rather wonderful. I prefer to leave rooms empty otherwise.  "You are the average of the 5 people you spend the most time with".  If you are here, you are already an honoured guest.
transit: The bus stop is a 3 minute walk away, on Parramatta road. Busses come every five minutes or so.  Its 10 minutes to Central station, 15 to the city of-peak, but be careful at peak times. It once took me 40 minutes. Its about 40 to the airport by Uber, about 17 minutes.  Otherwise, take the bus to Central Station, then train, which takes about 45 minutes total.
access: You can use the kitchen for your breakfast, and other meals by arrangement.  There is a shared bathroom across from your room, we are all thoughtful, yielding people. Check in is from 4pm.  If you want to check in earlier, just ask. If its possible, we will arrange something.
interaction: I mostly I choose guests admire and enjoy, so hanging out together, or complete privacy are both options that work super-well.  Because I'm into food, we usually end up cooking at least one healthy meal together. The main living room is a place you can socialise with other extraordinary guests, the second living room is a private spot you can make phone calls in, get on your laptop and go crazy with work.
house_rules: Use thoughtful observation, and we will all be fine.
host_about:
I'm a permaculture designer and Illustrator, with a serious commitment to making my world luscious. So far, so good, thanks to the excellent people who come and stay in my house, and who let me into theirs, long before AirB&B.

I've  living and working part of each year in Australia, part in Tokyo, and little working trips all over the place.

I write a Magazine column in Japanese, 'Cecilia's Permacutlure Slow Life'. Its about creative ways to de-trap your life of wasted time, energy and affection, freeing you up to do the good work you were put on this world to do. 

For 9 years Ive run a share-house for creative people - you can read about it on my Blog Balcony Garden dreaming

My hobbies are Sado (Japanese tea eremony), balcony gardening, fancy dress parties, and drawing illustrations of the quirky world I would like to live in, and often actually do.  These are also my jobs.

Ive been a WWOOF host and traveler for many years (willing workers on organic farms). Even when my farm was just a balcony garden. 

I don't have a life motto exactly, but when thing go wrong, I ask myself 'Whiner or designer?', and that gets me positive and resourceful, finding a way to make things better.
If things go wrong for you I won't say it though. I'll just help where I can xx

Exposed beams and distressed hardwood floors, immediate access to the outdoors on the huge balcony, and a view of the Sears --ahem-- 'Willis' Tower from bed. neighborhood_overview: I just finished creating a very detailed map of the neighborhood of all my favorite places to eat and drink as well as public transportation stops, all sorts of other tips for getting around the city. I'll provide a link to the map upon booking. Great eats: Dusek's, Punch House, Nightwood, Skylark, Bodhi Thai, Honky Tonk BBQ, etc. etc. etc... East Pilsen AKA Chicago's Historic Arts District has lots of cool galleries and is perhaps best known for its open gallery walks where you can check out a tons of galleries or open art studios and see all sorts of art made by local artists. Peppered with rad wall murals and vibrant and diverse cultures I definitely think Pilsen is one of the best neighborhoods to call home in Chicago. (Hence, my address.) 1.5 miles from Mccormick Place. Great place to stay while in town for an expo or convention to be close by but still get to take in this great neighborhood.
notes: Smoking indoors is not cool. Smoking on the balcony is totally fine.
transit: Highway 90/94 is just a few blocks away which is the main artery to most other parts of the city. The Red Line is the closest train stop and the nearby  Halsted bus puts you right into the West Loop and a number of other train options. Cabs roll around occasionally but Uber cabs are way cheaper and far more convenient. Also, there is a Divvy bike station within a block and I'm just a few blocks from the Chinatown water taxi stop in Ping Tom Park along the Chicago River.
access: The place is all yours for as long as your stay lasts. You'll have access to the second floor balcony which is shared with 2 stellar neighbors/close friends. The balcony overlooks a private courtyard area which you are also free to use. Washer and dryer in the atrium on the ground floor are 1.75 per wash and 1.50 per dry. There is a main entrance to the building which takes you through the tropical atrium though there is easier and more private access on the east side of the building which is the most convenient (though less scenic) entrance.
interaction: I'm available via text and email around the clock. Depending on when you are coming to stay, I will do everything I can to meet you personally, but if it's not possible, the keys will be handed off by a trusted friend. I'll also be sure to provide loads of info on how best to get around, options of what to do and see while you're here and detailed instructions on how to use any of the items in the house that may require additional explanation like the digital movie projector or the juicer.
house_rules: Just be respectful. My neighbors are close friends and we treat each other and the shared spaces with respect and are always considerate of everyone else in the building. That being said, there's never a need to tiptoe or worry about playing music at a reasonable volume. Have fun and use good judgment.
host_about:
I'm an outgoing and friendly freelance photographer. In my photography work I focus mainly on travel, live music, interior design and architecture as well as various other forms of commercial photography to keep the bills paid.

I was born and raised in Cincinnati, Ohio and moved to Chicago 11 years ago. Aside from a few months spent in Nicaragua after college, a few months in Buenos Aires, Argentina, and a month in Tokyo in 2015, I've stayed and absolutely loved living in Chicago. Other travels have included Prague, Italy, Mexico, Spain, Panama, Costa Rica, Japan, Uruguay, Thailand, Vietnam, Cambodia and I'm gearing up for a very exciting few weeks photographing and filming in Kenya and Rwanda for a documentary series about extraordinary women doing great things around the world. 

I enjoy cooking but not as much as I like going out to dinner. I am equally as comfortable in a dive bar drinking cheap beer at the pool table as I am in a high end restaurant drinking fine wine and whiskey. Though, in an ideal world I would be sipping fine wine or whiskey at the dive bar pool table.

I see A LOT of live music, partially because I photograph a lot of musician portraits and live concerts for various publications, but ultimately just because I enjoy many types of music very much. 

I love meeting new people from all over the world and hope we get to meet very soon.

summary: We feel lucky to live on a compound of cottages in the middle of the best part of Venice Beach. It feels like community and we  cannot think of a better place to live.
space: The compound itself is made up of seven units, four of them 40’s cottages and two of those are now offered as vacation rentals. One bedroom cottage in a secluded garden compound of friendly, arty, Venice types. 

Vaulted ceilings, hardwood floors, free bikes, boards, cable, wifi, laundry machines, gated parking for one car. Pets are warmly welcomed and roam safely behind the fence.

Recently highlighted on the Venice House & Garden Tour. Two fire pits, six fountains, seven kinds of bamboo, dogs running, chicken scratching… 
we think it's perfect for a certain kind of person.

130/day (minimum 5 days). 830/week, 3,500/month,  60 maid deposit. 

Any questions try calling us 310 and 581 and 7951.

Chiyoko was born in Tokyo and was an editor and journalist. She was the US correspondent for a major Japanese music magazine. She is now into healthy cooking, pottery, blogging and gardening.

Allan was born in a small town in Quebec north of Montreal. He dropped out of McGill to travel the world, ended up writing and directing movies first in NYC and then in LA. 

Allan's top influential movies are  Husbands, Nashville, 400 Blows.  All time fave is Performance.

Chiyoko's top five movies are Taxidriver, Moulin Rouge, Little Miss Sunshine, Roman Holiday and Dazed And Confused. Scariest is Midnight Express.

Your Space *night stand  *AC and/or heat *clean sheets and towels  *great natural light throughout house *incredibly spacious *games *books and magazine Guest Access ★Amenities★  - Wifi Internet  - Cooking ware, plates, cups, utensils - Iron & Ironing Board  -Coffee, tea -Back yard fire pit -Front porch for relaxing All guests have full access to the kitchen, laundry room, bathroom, front and back yard. Our home is a bright, po
neighborhood_overview: We live in a quaint friendly neighborhood! It's not "hipsterville" or super trendy, but it's super safe, and I love it!  You will often see kids playing in the streets all day on the weekends, but for the most part it's pretty quiet.  We're not in the hub of things, but we are only 10 - 15 minute drive away from all things exciting in Nashville!
notes: We have two dogs that are permanent fixtures at the house, and one that comes and goes with my boyfriend on occasion. Our dogs are super well behaved and very sweet. Junior (the pup) is very friendly and loving. Sasha is a cuddle bug, and if you let her, will curl up in your lap like a baby and live there....forever. Haha! Red (the boyfriend's dog) does his own thing when he comes over. He's very sweet, but normally not interested in much, and just sleeps in my room. They  spend most of their time wherever I happen to be in the house, but they do like to say hello to our guests if they hear you in a common area. You must love dogs if you plan on staying here!  Everyone always loves our dogs, and are really impressed by how well behaved they are. We run a tight doggy ship here. :)) Also, please note that we do have another room that we rent out. So there's a good chance that there are other guests in the house. It never seems to be an issue, as everyone is normally off enjoying Nashvill
transit: If you do not have a vehicle, we have public transportation that picks up right on our street. Also, it's only about a 10 - 15 Uber or Lyft ride to East Nashville, Downtown, West End, etc (all of the places worth going)! Otherwise, we are about 10 - 15 minutes away from everywhere you need to go in the city! It's quite convenient!
access: All guests have full access to the kitchen, laundry room, bathroom, front and back yard.
interaction: Our home is a bright, positive, and creative atmosphere. I have an art studio in the extra room, so I will most often be in there or outside painting or working on my latest project. My boyfriend, Paul, drops in frequently, but is not a permanent fixture in my home. He is very personable and friendly, and will most likely want to talk with you about his farming and Monolithic Domes, if you're interested. :) I am very busy for the most part, but I am always available if you need me. You can call or text me for anything at all throughout the day if I'm not around. When I am at home, I always enjoy interacting with my guests; if they're willing! Most of all, I will insure that you have a positive and fun experience staying at my place!
house_rules: I am pretty laid back. All I ask is that you're respectful of my place, and if you're coming in ultra late that you're respectful and conscious of the amount of noise you make.  Other than that, please make yourselves at home!
host_about:
I am a free spirited artist with a strong sense of self.  I dream big and pursue without doubt.  I love to laugh and I try not to take myself or tough situations too seriously. I'm passionate about everything I do, and try to surround myself with equally passionate people. 

I'm incredibly laid back, but I'm also very outgoing and social. I love being around people. I have traveled to most major cities in the US, and very few out of the country. However, I am ready to see the world! My dream destination is Tokyo, Japan, amongst many others. 

I love hosting and meeting new people while sharing and learning about their experiences and lives. As a host, I share my space openly and create a fun and positive environment for my guests. Everyone feels at home, and most feel as if we've known each other for a lifetime. As a guest, I am respectful, clean, interactive, cheerful and always grateful!

My motto in life is, "She who dares, wins!"

name: PARADISE ROOM w. BALCONY - BOUTIQUE HOTEL LUXURY
summary: WELCOME HOME IN MY PARADISE ROOM WITH ITS PRIVATE BALCONY! Enjoy your stay in my elegant, light-filled 120m2 apartment with loft character & extravagant interior design in a listed 1910 'Art Nouveau' building.  Located in a quiet residential area opposite beautiful green Treptower Park, yet close to hip X-berg, Neukölln & Friedrichshain. Guaranteed easy access to Berlin's public transportation system from S-Bahn 'Treptower Park', 12min walk from my home.  FOR GUESTS WITH DISTINGUISHED TASTE!
space: The guest room on offer here in this particular listing is called "The PARADISE room",  which references the hummingbird pattern on the Osborn & Little wallpaper in this room. It is otherwise used as my library and room for study.  This room has a great totally comfortable and recently upholstered sofa bed (165cm wide) which comfortably sleeps 2 people.  This room has access to a balcony facing East, so the sun may wake you in the morning  unless you close the  fuchsia colored silk curtains which immerses the room an incredible warm glow in the morning.   The second bedroom available for booking in a second airbnb listing is called "The UNICORN Room" size 14sqm, has a proper 160cm wide bed, again designed for 2 people and en-suite bathroom with bath tub.  My place is suitable for parties of up to 4 people if both rooms are still available.  The literal center piece of the apartment is a 40sqm living kitchen with balcony to cook, eat, meet other guest and myself and hang out. Everything

neighborhood_overview: I absolutely adore the area I live in!!! It's super green, safe and quiet with the park and the small lake just across the street, you can walk to river Spree across the park.  At the same time, it"s really close to all the happening areas, Kreuzberg, Neukölln and Friedrichshain. If you don"t want to walk there or take a taxi, feel free to use my bicyles to get around!
notes: One important reminder at this point:  I am a dog lover and my adorable dog Luna lives me in my flat. I do not believe that dogs are in any way unhygienic, at least not more than humans.  It is unavoidable despite all efforts to clean and hover the flat that there will be places where you spot dog hair.  If that is something that bothers or concerns you, I recommend looking for alternative options.
transit: My place is conveniently located to public transport: closest S-bahn station is "Treptower Park" on the ring (circle) train  10min leisurely walk  through the park and bus stop just outside of the house
access: I like my guests to feel 'at home away from home'.  With that, there are no limits to communal areas and rooms they can access or use, as long as they keep them clean and ready for use by others.  I appreciate if guests are not hiding in their room and keeping to themselves but I do encourage them to share the public spaces.  On the same note, I expect that guests do not regard their room as their private property and accept that I may have to access the room to get some things or occasionally use it while they are not using it themselves.  I am looking at this more than a shared flat with temporary guests than a hotel where people check in, do their thing and check out.  Of course, mutual respect and trust is the basis for this kind of openness which is both granted  by myself as well as expected from my guests.
interaction: The level of interaction with my guests generally depends on a range of different factors such as my guest's travel plans, my own work and social calendar how much interaction we will have. Generally speaking, I do find the social dimension of AirBnB at least equally attractive as the financial award as a host. Therefore, I do not like guests to treat me as an employee in a hotel that will do the check-in and check-out but would like to remind everyone that for whatever limited time we have, we are sharing together this space, with me included. Interaction and communication between us make these moments much more valuable and interesting for both myself and my guests.  I greatly enjoy sharing with my guests my story, my view of Berlin, favorite places, clubs, art venues, cafes, neighborhoods and the reasons why I love this city more than any other.   The fascinating thing for me is this: I always learn something new from my guests that I did not know, experienced or paid attention to!
house_rules: I kindly ask my guest to respect the following house rules:  1. Kindly remove your shoes when entering the flat, I am happy to provide some extra shoes for the house. That protects the antique wooden parquet floor and reduces the noise level for my downstairs neighbor.  2. Smoking is not permitted inside the flat, only on both balconies. 3. Please respect my neighbors and avoid excessive noise in the flat, particularly between 10pm and 8am. This also includes the staircase when you return late at night.  NOTE: my downstairs neighbor has his bedroom under my kitchen. Noise travels more easily in an old house like mine. I recommend using the living room when you want to sit together in the evening to have drinks.  4. Parties are explicitly NOT allowed, unless you have prior approval, particularly if it involves inviting non-guests to the flat.  5. Please keep the kitchen area clean and tidy, put away into the dishwasher or wash any dirty dishes. 6. One last important house rule for MALE
host_about:
Hi there, I am George and proud to be AirBnB Superhost for the 10th time in a row! I love hosting people from all over the world. 
What I enjoyed most during my 18-month travel around the world a few years ago was to spend time with friends who were kind enough to host me in their homes (San Francisco, Tokyo, Miami, Rio de Janeiro just to name a few). Now that I have settled down in my favorite city Berlin, I love to return the  favor and open up my place to guests from other countries and cultures to make it their home away from home.
I am a gay man, currently living by myself  with my adorable dog Luna, a German short hair pointer after my longtime Brazilian partner from Rio de Janeiro moved out to start a degree in 'Fashion Branding'  @ Amsterdam Fashion Institute (AmFI). I have always enjoyed hosting other people, showing them my city and sharing with them my view of Berlin, what to do and how to make the most of their time. 
Professionally, I work as an business consultant for a big American company. As a balance for my creative half I like art (both visiting exhibitions as well as getting my own small eclectic collection), going for long walks with my dog in the country side around Berlin, architecture, traveling, enjoying the amazing cultural offers in Berlin ranging from opera to nights (and days) in my favorite club Berghain. But above all, I am  a huge fan of Franco-Belgian comics such as Tintin, Blake & Mortimer, Sopie & Starter etc. Not only do I collect these comics but I also collect art work such as Aroutcheff toys, cars and vehicles. 
The other passion is decorating my apartement with rare antiques and art work. It makes me proud that virtually anyone who comes to visit immediately falls in love with my flat. 
My favorite author is Haruki Murakami, about time he gets the Nobel prize for literature! Favorite destinations are Nepal, Japan and Easter Islands. 
If I am not busy enjoying the cultural attractions of Berlin, I love watching well made US series e.g. Sopranos, The Wire and Game of Thrones. 
Favorite directors are Pedro Almodovar, David Lynch, Jim Jarmusch and Francois Truffeaut. 
If you stay with me, you should not be afraid of dogs. I would like my guests to really feel at home at my place and invite them to the  entire space rather than just their room for cooking, relaxing, borrowing my books or taking a sun bath on one of my balconies. 
My leitmotiv is "Work hard & party hard" and "Live and let live", I am tolerant towards other views and opinions as long as they do the same. I hate intolerant and hypocritical people who think they have eaten the truth with a spoon. Gay and lesbian friendly!
street: Plänterwald, Berlin, Berlin 12435, Germany

summary: This lovely first floor flat is  500 metres from Canada Water underground and overground station and a stones throw from the River Thames.  There is one double room and a twin room.  Suitable for an individual stay as well as a family holiday.
space: This spacious 2 bedroom flat is on the first floor of a purpose built apartment block.  There is a double bedroom and a twin room, both are light and airy and have been newly decorated. Whether you are a lone traveller, on business, or a family on a city bre
neighborhood_overview: I love how quiet it is around Canada Water, despite it being so close to the station.  2 minutes away - running along the back of the flats is a little river that leads to the River Thames. Here you will find a gorgeous modern English pub, the Old Salt Quay, which serves traditional and very tasty food. It also has seating outside for an amazing view of the Thames. The flat is also one stop away from Canary Wharf on the jubilee line, where not only will you find yourself in London's iconic centre of business, there is also a cinema, loads of restaurants, a good shopping centre, bowling alley, a huge Supermarket - ALL less than 10 minutes away!! If you are planning to go to a concert at the O2 Arena, this is only 2 stops away on the underground to North Greenwich.
notes: We are a LGBT friendly household.
transit: As previously mentioned, the flat is 500 metres from Canada Water station. If you are coming from Heathrow, you jump on the Piccadilly line heading towards Arnos Grove.  Change at Green park for the Jubilee line towards Stratford and get off at Canada Water station. From Gatwick, jump on the Gatwick express to Victoria, then Victoria line to Green park. Get on the Jubilee line towards Stratford.  Get off at Canada Water station. From Luton airport.  Take the train to Kings Cross.  Take the Northern line, south bound to London Bridge, change to the jubilee line towards Stratford and get off at Canada Water. Stanstead airport.  You can get a National Express  bus from the airport to Stratford, then get on the jubilee line to Canada Water.   Alternatively, you can get the Stanstead express to London Liverpool Street, take the underground on the Hammersmith & City line, to whitechapel, change to the overground 2 stops heading south to Canada Water.
access: Whether you are a lone traveller, on business, or a family on a city break, this flat is fully equipped for all your needs.   The flat is self contained and will be yours to have exclusive access to during your stay.  As mentioned in 'the space', the large communal garden is shared with other residents - sadly no ball games or BBQs are allowed in the garden.
interaction: I will be there to greet you upon your arrival and hand over keys, and I will come at the end of your stay to collect the keys.  Then the rest is up to you!  There will be all the relevant information in the flat and I am always just a phone call away.
house_rules: Although you have the use of the whole flat.  I ask that you respect that there are other flat owners in the building and keep the noise to a minimum.  This is a non smoking building and I'm sorry we cannot accommodate any pets.
host_about:
Hi I'm a 50 year old woman.  I have been a plumber for 10 years.  I run my own small plumbing business called Princess Plumbing.   I have travelled extensively including Thailand, Most of Europe, Canada, Us, Caribbean, including living in Australia for 4 years.  My favourite place being Tokyo, Japan. love good food, good wine and good company.  
I've been an airbnb host for 2 years now so used to meeting people from all over the world.  Hilda is the housekeeper of the flat, so if it's not me greeting you and exchanging keys, Hilda will be there.  She lives 2 minutes from the flat.  Having previously been a professional singer, I have performed in several west end shows, I am familiar with what shows are good and how to get cheap tickets.

neighborhood_overview: The Canary Wharf area is traditionally known to be the beating heart of London’s financial sector, full of tall buildings housing international banks. In recent years though, a large number of restaurants and bars have popped up in the area (and would be an easy 15-20 minute walk from the flat), such as Obica, Iberica, and Royal China. I particularly like Chai Ki, a modern Indian restaurant. You can also get drinks or have afternoon tea at the lovely Radisson Blu hotel nearby the apartment complex, which is a great setting to meet friends. Or, you can just use the kitchen in the apartment to cook yourself a meal and enjoy a nice comfy stay. With an iconic skyline towering over London, striking and dynamic architecture and a vibrant, cosmopolitan feel, Canary Wharf is firmly established as a first class shopping and leisure destination There are plenty of bars, pubs, restaurants, luxury stores to shop and a massive shopping mall.  Canary Wharf is a major business district located in Tow

My name is Fabio and I along with my friend and colleague Willian will ensure to provide you a wonderful stay in our apartments across London.

Willian, Throughout his extensive travels, his unusual name – a derivative of William – has led to much curiosity. An Ecuadorian by birth, He has added to my higher education internationally, with economic studies in the USA, language training in Japan, and a BA and MBA in the United Kingdom.

I am a 37 year old professional, currently working and living in London, Willian is 30 year old professional, currently working and living in lively London. the most exciting and bigger property market in the world. During all this description of myself well mostly Willian, you will find out how travelling could probably be Willian's and I number 1 hobbie. Although, We do not see it as a hobby but a luxury :). We do also enjoy playing sports, attending concerts, going to the movies, clubbing, hanging out, cooking and much more! 

Airbnb is awesome. Willian remembers his first time using the portal was back in 2010, when he travelled to Tokyo to attend an university interview over there. He had booked an comfortable duplex apartment in Shinjuku from this lovely Japanese guy, Junichi. He was amazed to see the true meaning of hospitality, being a host is more than just being the doorman or the typical receptionist at concierge, it is being someone who receives, treat and entertains other people as guests. 

All my life Willian and I have dedicated quite a lot of time to travel around the globe where We have had the opportunity to meet amazing people and experienced other cultures, costumes, and more. That is exactly why I am currently working in the hospitality industry with my colleague and friend Fabio because what I have learned all these years travelling around is that hospitality is the friendly and generous reception and entertainment of guests, visitors, or strangers not matter where people come from.

Fabio and I look forward welcoming and hosting some many guest in the upcoming years. I will truly give you my 100% to ensure your stay goes very well why you are staying at my apartments. I hope you enjoy the experience and adventure and thank you in advance :).

Your hosts,
Willian - Fabio

neighborhood_overview: Portobello Market in West London is one of the most famous street markets in the world. It is a popular destination for Londoners and tourists alike. Portobello Road goes straight through the heart of Notting Hill, the trendy area of London made famous by the film. Indeed, so famous is the film Notting Hill that I find scarcely a week goes by without someone or other asking me about the various set locations: the blue door, the travel bookshop, the garden fence and so on. Portobello Market takes up most of what is actually more properly called Portobello Road, it stretches for around two miles, although on a crowded saturday afternoon it takes quite a while to walk from end to end.
transit: Getting to Notting Hill by Bus There are also many buses operating across the whole of Notting Hill, including routes (phone number hidden) and 452 amongst others – take a look at Transport for London’s Kensington & Chelsea Bus Route maps for more details. You’ll find that buses operate right through Notting Hill, with many servicing some of the area’s main larger roads such as Notting Hill Gate, Westbourne Grove, Kensington Park Road, Pembridge Villas, Ladbroke Road, Westbourne Park Road and more. You can easily reach Notting Hill by bus if you’re travelling from Chelsea, Kensington, South Kensington, Knightsbridge, Shepherd’s Bush and Paddington. There are also a number of buses from further afield…but as the journey time can be considerable (taking into account the London traffic), we’d advise taking the Underground instead!

Although so much is happening around us, we are tucked away in a quiet, safe neighborhood. Once inside, our home feels more like a Northern California retreat even though we are located in a SoCal urban, hot spot. Walking distance from Trader Joe's and Gelson's supermarket you will never have to worry about not having everything you need to be comfortable. We are located right in between trendy Sunset Junction  and Los Feliz Village. Sunset Junction is known for it's amazing farmer's market, restaurants, bars, boutique shops, bakeries and more (you can borrow our bike if you want to really feel like a local). notes: As mentioned several times, this is our family home. We have two young children who live upstairs. We are very busy during the week so you will not hear from us much between 7:30a.m. and 4p.m. However we are early risers, 7 a.m., and you may hear us getting ready for school during the weekdays.  Weekends we are often home. You will hear us going about our business upstairs. Your floor is very private, and we cannot access it if you have it locked. People traveling with children can feel free to send their children outside to play any time. Our backyard is enclosed and full of fun nature activities! We have a tire swing and a shed full of toys!

If you want any entertainment or restaurant tips ask away!

Lots of plug ins, hi speed internet, huge 65"TV with my netflix account hooked in....I've tried to think of everything. host_about:
Hello World! 

Travel has been a big part of my life. I was raised in Melbourne and although it is one of my favourite cities... I do try to escape at least once a year to discover somewhere new. 

Holiday Highlights include: Hitch-hiking around Alaska & Canada, Yoga & surf retreats in Bali, La Sagrada Familia in Barcelona, the cenotes & margaritas of Mexico. I've Managed a Backpackers Hostel in Canada, served Guinness in Belfast & snowboarded in Austria, Canada, New Zealand & Japan. 

I also trained as a Ninja in Tokyo ;)

I love to immerse myself in a place to discover & experience sights, food, markets, music, activities and local life. It's meeting the locals & other explorers along the way that has enriched these experiences.

This is why I am excited to be a host to fellow travellers.

Welcome to Melbourne :)

The area is safe but some of the challenges of the area (mental health, drug addiction) are apparent. Two blocks away you are in the midst of Gastown with it's interesting architecture and vibrant restaurants, galleries and shops: (website hidden)
notes: I would like to give you what I believe is a fair and accurate overview of the area to help inform your decision. The area I live in, Japantown, is one of the oldest areas of Vancouver with a rich history. It is also an area where many social services and low income housing was created. As such there are people with drug addiction, prostitution and other related challenges. That said, the area has been undergoing a transition with artist studios, high tech startups (until recently Hoot Suite was in the hood) and some cool coffee shops and restaurants opening up. I personally live here and I like the community and have always felt safe, as do the young professionals that rent out suites in my building. Area restaurants/features: Ask Luigi Belgard Kitchen Cuchillo The location is great with just a short walk to Gastown, the happening entertainment area. Downtown is also close and easily accessible by foot and bus. There is also a beautiful park within 7 minutes walk, right on the water w
transit: There are multiple bus routes within 3 blocks that take you downtown in minutes and also access the Skytrains (Main & Terminal or Waterfront Station). Walking is also a breeze and you can be in the heart of downtown, walking through beautiful Gastown, within 20 minutes.

house_rules: There is a stereo and home theatre which you are welcome to use. The tenants in the building are friendly and helpful but mostly you won't likely see them much. I just ask you don't crank the sound too high, especially after 11.

notes: The LA County Museum of Art is a 5 minute drive away.  The Farmer's Market and Grove with unique shopping and entertainment are a 7 minute drive away.  You can walk to shops and cafes on Pico Blvd within 5 minutes.
transit: A major bus depot is a 15 minute walk from the unit.  Also bus lines run along Wilshire Blvd., Pico, Fairfax and LaBrea which are all between 5 and 10 minutes away.  The new Expo line which runs from Downtown to Santa Monica is a 7 minute drive from the unit.
access: Private garden area with seating.  There is a digital combination door lock, so late check in is easy to accommodate.
interaction: Little interaction by landlord with guests.
house_rules: No smoking, no loud parties.  We request that you take off your shoes in the unit.  No pets.  Kids are welcome.   Also, please do not put any food scraps larger then your fingernail down the disposal, nothing beside toilet paper down the toilet, and clear the tub drain of any hair after you shower.  The building was built in 1939 and the pipes require extra TLC to stay blockage-free. Quiet hours are 10:00pm to 8am.  No loud talking outside the unit.  It's a quiet, friendly, respectful neighborhood, so if you're this type of guest you'll be very happy!

neighborhood_overview: Northcote is a buzzy, happening neighbourhood. Separation Street is an active street that links directly with the main drag of High Street, about 8 mins walk from the house. This has everything including a large shopping plaza, but its vibe is more about boutique, cool little shops and bars. There's several live music venues, cool bars, and a good selection of options for eating out. The suburbs either side are Westgarth and Thornbury, which also have good places to eat and drink. The bus out the front goes to Brunswick which is a cultural eating mecca with yet more bars and shops (!), and Fitzroy is just 4 minutes away, with more buzz and things to do, including a range of good galleries. CBD is about 14 mins on the train. Whilst we are in the thick of action, the All Nations Park behind our house has several kid's playgrounds, native bush plantings, and loads of open space. At the far end of our street, approx 4 mins drive, is the Darebin Parklands, a massive green wedge of native bu
notes: There is a minimum 3 night stay, and we are open to negotiating longer term stays for the listed period.  NOTE: the listed price is for 4 guests. We can accommodate up to 5 guests however with a single camping bed or the couch is a modular that easily accommodates an adult. There is an extra 30 p/ night for 5 guests. Babies: no charge!
transit: We are in public transport central! Bus out the front, tram about 8 mins walk away which goes to the CBD and on to the beach in St Kilda. Or there's the train station approx 15 mins walk away (or 3 stops on the bus) which is about 14 mins from the CBD. If you have a car, we are very close to the Eastern and South Eastern freeways, which link to Melbourne's beautiful Dandenongs, and to the Mornington Peninsula.
access: Guests have access to everything that they can see in the house, including vegie garden produce, plus wi fi. We supply fresh bed linen and towels, soap, cooking utensils and some basic pantry items.
interaction: We will be available on email at least once a day and there is a phone number for emergencies.
house_rules: This is our family home. Please treat it with care and respect!
host_about:
I'm a Marketing and Events Manager at a community radio station in Melbourne. I also study Anthropology part time, am a musician, and I'm way into food and gardening too.

My partner and my 3 year old daughter are heading to Japan. This will be my partner's 5th trip to Tokyo- he has good friends there. This is my second trip to Japan and our daughter's first time! My partner and I are pretty well travelled, but this will be our first time sourcing accom on Air BnB. 

The plan for this trip is to stay in Tokyo for a few days before heading to Shikinejima for a week. We're hoping to camp on the beach. Then back to Tokyo for 3 days and then home. Am really looking forward to some great food and time to hang out and read.

neighborhood_overview: Located in Melbourne's east, Doncaster is one of the nicer areas of Melbourne. Our home is on a quiet, multicultural neighbourhood surrounded by local parks. You can find many Chinese, Italian, Greek, Persian, Malaysian, Thai, Vietnamese and Japanese restaurants in the area. Supermarkets and Asian groceries are also easily accessible. The famous Ruffey Lake Park is just opposite our home where you can take beautiful walks while watching the sunrise or the sunset. The park is fully equipped with all the facilities you need for a great day out, with picnic tables and chairs, barbecues, rubbish bins and public toilets. There is plenty of other outdoor pursuits to satisfy everyone's craving for fresh air and nature. Walking trails take you throughout the whole park, with some quite challenging sections as the paths head up and over the rolling hills. Take the bus direct to the city, to Westfield Shoppingtown (which has over 500+ shops!) or to other attractions and places of interest.   Bus routes also link to Melbourne's extended public transport network - Victoria is your oyster! There are 2 Myki cards that you can borrow, you just need to top up with  dollars and tap on and off as you go (bus, trams & trains).

name: Treetop Suite at Zen Fairyland
summary: Climb the stairs, and you are in a world of your own. A luxury Queen bed, modern ensuite bathroom and forest view is yours.   Its a house with Japanese levels of thoughtfulness, good people, and a cute cat and chickens.
space: This home was made for people who are busy changing the world, or at least their part of it, and need a leafy green re-charge, right here.   The main room is airy and high-ceilinged.  There is a cute cat, and 3 chickens roam the garden. They will give you an egg for breakfast.  All this peacefulness is just 10 minutes to Sydney Central Station. Our house is semi-Japanese. That means, we aspire to be super-observant, doing the small things that matter. Like keeping your room crisp and restful, and making you happy. I usually have live-in assistants who help keep the place nice, and you looked after. We often do easy yoga in the evenings, and you will be invited to join in.  There is no T.V. here, that helps keep the place peaceful, and the human connections rich and lively.

notes: If you look at the profiles of my past guests, you will notice they are all rather wonderful.  I prefer to leave rooms empty otherwise.  "You are the average of the 5 people you spend the most time with".   If you are here, you are already an honoured guest.
transit: Its 4 minutes walk to the Bus stop on Parramatta road, with busses to the city every 5 minutes. We have beaut bikes you can borrow, by arrangement.
access: Feel free to use the kitchen for your breakfasts, and you dinners too, by arrangement before booking.  We will make a spot for you to keep your ingredients. Check in is from 4pm.  If you want an earlier check-in, just ask and we will arrange it for you, wherever possible.
interaction: As much or little as they wish.  I choose guests who I admire and enjoy,  so our interactions are meaningful and fun. Because of the Japanese culture, we are good at yielding to each other, to make life collision free. There are other wonderful, thoughtful volunteers and housemates living here, and are a joy to live with, even if you hardly see each other.
house_rules: I always choose great people.  You already know how to be a thoughtful, observant guest, no worries. Dinner parties of wonderful guests are possible. The furniture bond amount would change, so would the nightly rate.
host_about:
I'm a permaculture designer and Illustrator, with a serious commitment to making my world luscious. So far, so good, thanks to the excellent people who come and stay in my house, and who let me into theirs, long before AirB&B.

I've  living and working part of each year in Australia, part in Tokyo, and little working trips all over the place.

I write a Magazine column in Japanese, 'Cecilia's Permacutlure Slow Life'. Its about creative ways to de-trap your life of wasted time, energy and affection, freeing you up to do the good work you were put on this world to do. 

For 9 years Ive run a share-house for creative people - you can read about it on my Blog Balcony Garden dreaming

My hobbies are Sado (Japanese tea eremony), balcony gardening, fancy dress parties, and drawing illustrations of the quirky world I would like to live in, and often actually do.  These are also my jobs.

Ive been a WWOOF host and traveler for many years (willing workers on organic farms). Even when my farm was just a balcony garden. 

I don't have a life motto exactly, but when thing go wrong, I ask myself 'Whiner or designer?', and that gets me positive and resourceful, finding a way to make things better.
If things go wrong for you I won't say it though. I'll just help where I can xx

neighborhood_overview: The Arts District is known for interesting bars, restaurants & entertainment, art galleries, high-end coffee shops and boutique shopping.  The scale of the neighborhood is very walkable and bike-able.  Industrial, yet charming aesthetics abound.  Diverse crowd - especially at night.  Also, Little Tokyo is about a 5 minute walk away and is a goldmine of interesting Japanese restaurants, karaoke and shopping.
notes: This apartment requires walking up 4 flights of stairs.  There is a freight elevator, but it not conveniently accessible. Since the loft is on the 4th floor of an apartment building we ask that guests are considerate of neighbors regarding noise level.  This apartment is a beloved home, so please be respectful.
transit: Super walkable neighborhood.  Biking is also great.  Lyft/Uber are easy here.  The nearest subway station is the Little Tokyo/Art District Station (Metro Gold Line) and is about a 5-7 minute walk from the building. Additionally, the DASH bus stop is 2 blocks from the building, which goes to the historic core section of downtown.
access: Laundry is available on the basement floor via the freight elevator.
interaction: Myself and my assistant typically meet guests upon check-in and are available via text/phone for questions and any issues that arise.  The written apartment guide located in the space has suggestions for restaurants, bars, groceries, and details about wifi, etc.
house_rules: No smoking, pets, or parties in the building.  Guests must be respectful of neighbors, especially regarding noise/volume.  No commercial filming. No candles or incense.

My husband Javier and I love to travel. Javier is from Madrid and I am a Santa Monica native. I have lived in Nepal and Thailand, each for a month, London for a year and Japan for almost 4 years working for the Japanese government as an English teacher.  Between us we speak English, French, Spanish and some Japanese. We encourage families to visit our home.  We have two boys.

I have a BFA in fine art and before having children I started my own business with the money I saved in Japan doing decorative painting in high end homes. Gold leaf, sky ceilings, lime wash finishes, frescoes, egg tempera and other decorative finishes. I LOVE to paint, design and draw! 

Javier and I are also crazy about Japanese design and we are inspired by the culture, architecture and food. Maybe you will feel a Japanese sensibility when you visit?

host_about:
My name is Fabio and I along with my friend and colleague Willian will ensure to provide you a wonderful stay in our apartments across London.

Willian, Throughout his extensive travels, his unusual name – a derivative of William – has led to much curiosity. An Ecuadorian by birth, He has added to my higher education internationally, with economic studies in the USA, language training in Japan, and a BA and MBA in the United Kingdom.

I am a 37 year old professional, currently working and living in London, Willian is 30 year old professional, currently working and living in lively London. the most exciting and bigger property market in the world. During all this description of myself well mostly Willian, you will find out how travelling could probably be Willian's and I number 1 hobbie. Although, We do not see it as a hobby but a luxury :). We do also enjoy playing sports, attending concerts, going to the movies, clubbing, hanging out, cooking and much more! 

Airbnb is awesome. Willian remembers his first time using the portal was back in 2010, when he travelled to Tokyo to attend an university interview over there. He had booked an comfortable duplex apartment in Shinjuku from this lovely Japanese guy, Junichi. He was amazed to see the true meaning of hospitality, being a host is more than just being the doorman or the typical receptionist at concierge, it is being someone who receives, treat and entertains other people as guests. 

All my life Willian and I have dedicated quite a lot of time to travel around the globe where We have had the opportunity to meet amazing people and experienced other cultures, costumes, and more. That is exactly why I am currently working in the hospitality industry with my colleague and friend Fabio because what I have learned all these years travelling around is that hospitality is the friendly and generous reception and entertainment of guests, visitors, or strangers not matter where people come from.

Fabio and I look forward welcoming and hosting some many guest in the upcoming years. I will truly give you my 100% to ensure your stay goes very well why you are staying at my apartments. I hope you enjoy the experience and adventure and thank you in advance :).

Your hosts,
Willian - Fabio

summary: First time in NY? Or visiting the kids for a weekend in Brooklyn? With free street parking, central air, and a balcony with grill and fire pit, this is the perfect home base. Grill a steak from the local butcher while you're up there. Turn on the fire pit if things get chilly after dark. Want to get creative with the ingredients from the local farmers market? There's an oven, microwave, high-speed blender, cast-iron cookware, spices, and a pair of very, very sharp knives. The sun-filled living room has a dining area, but you'd be foolish not to eat outside in the warm summer air. The room is large, clean, and faces away from the street. You'll wake up feeling refreshed on a queen-size Casper mattress and catch the sunrise from a private balcony. If traveling light isn't your forte, don't worry: there's plenty of closet space. The bathroom is yours and yours alone. No one deserves to share when they're on vacation. The L train is five blocks away with access to Manhattan

neighborhood_overview: Great mix of old-school Williamsburg classics, including lots of great Italian food, with newer, trendier places. Graham Ave. is lined with great restaurants, bars and cafes, boutique shopping, 24-hour delis, juice bars, and a fancy butcher shop. Bedford Ave. is a 15-minute walk, or a couple of minutes on the subway. It's the main attraction in Williamsburg, and thick with specialty coffee shops, boutiques, and restaurants competing for attention. It's also home to Smorgasburg, a famous outdoor food market in East River Park, and Music Hall of Williamsburg, one of the better small venues in town. McCarren Park is a short walk away, and is usually filled with young people on the weekends exercising, shopping at the local farmers market, and hanging out on the grass with their friends, kids, and dogs. To the West, Greenpoint is a 5-10 minute walk towards the river, and is filled with vintage stores, specialty restaurants, and other hidden gems. To the East, Bushwick's Morgan and Jefferso
notes: Smoker? No problem. You'll have access to balconies, including one in your room, that are sheltered from the elements.
transit: The L train will take you pretty much anywhere you want to get to in Brooklyn, Queens, or Manhattan. It's a 10-minute ride to Union Square.  The G train will take you into Queens (Court Square, Long Island City), or down into Bed Stuy, Fort Green, and you can transfer to the F train to get to DUMBO, Prospect Park, Park Slope, and Prospect Heights. There are also car services, and plenty of Ubers in the area.  If you'd like to bike, there are two Citi-Bike stands around the corner.
access: Guests have access to the entire first floor of the apartment, plus the upstairs balcony. Feel free to make use of the kitchen, fridge, oven, and anything else you need to feed yourself.
interaction: We live upstairs, but we're rarely home. You might see us in the kitchen making breakfast or dinner, but for the most part you'll have the entire place to yourself. We're not professional real-estate brokers, and this is our only listing. We love to host other travelers, and will do everything we can to make your stay as comfortable as possible. We'll be available anytime over text, phone, or the in-app messaging if you need assistance. We're also happy to help with recommendations for fun things to see and do! Larissa, my fiancee, is a journalist and covers events and cool things to do in New York. We look forward to hosting you.

host_about:
I grew up in a small suburb of Philadelphia, studied computer science and fine arts at the University of Pennsylvania, and spent time living in Melbourne and Rio de Janeiro before moving to New York. 

My last trip was two incredible weeks with my fiancée bouncing around Japan, including Tokyo, Kyoto, Hiroshima, and Osaka, with a pit stop in a hot springs resort town and a half-day on the deer-filled island of Miyajima.

I've been designing and building apps and web products for about 25 years, and have worked for The New York Times and VICE, in addition to doing a bunch of freelance consulting. 

Outside of work, I spend time hiking, volunteering, and hanging out in Brooklyn. I know Williamsburg in and out, and can always figure out something fun to do in the area on short notice.

neighborhood_overview: Your hosts made Madison Valley their home when settling in Seattle 5 years ago... and haven't looked back since. We love walking the streets of this neighborhood, and we will gladly suggest fun walks depending on your interests. Stroll to the beach at Madison Park. Walk by multi-million dollar estates. Discover hidden neighborhood gems such as the farmhouse with horses in the yard and the home that doubles as an eclectic art studio and antique truck gallery. Take a walk through the fabled Arboretum to Lake Washington. Once you have worked up your appetite, enjoy the countless restaurants that Madison Valley ("Little Paris") has to offer. In addition to French gems, try our favorite tapas restaurant or the best Japanese food east of Tokyo. Take your morning coffee in one of numerous bakeries. Or opt for Thai, pan-Asian, craft pizza, Tex-Mex or more. Our home provides easy access to Downtown (Pikes Place Market, Seattle Art Museum, Seattle Great Wheel), Seattle Center (Space Needle, Chih
notes: Is your group larger than this home will accommodate? We can host up to *78* guests across our portfolio --- with all homes located within a few blocks! host_about: My wife and I are world travelers.  We've traveled to ~60 countries around the world... on all 7 continents!  While we enjoy a fancy hotel now and then, nothing beats the comforts of a real HOME away from home.  Having rented countless vacation homes during our time, we have copious notes of what we do and don't like.  We aspire to make our Airbnb rental home an example of all the best traits we have found in our vacation rentals.

neighborhood_overview: The Canary Wharf area is traditionally known to be the beating heart of London’s financial sector, full of tall buildings housing international banks. In recent years though, a large number of restaurants and bars have popped up in the area (and would be an easy 15-20 minute walk from the flat), such as Obica, Iberica, and Royal China. I particularly like Chai Ki, a modern Indian restaurant. You can also get drinks or have afternoon tea at the lovely Radisson Blu hotel nearby the apartment complex, which is a great setting to meet friends. Or, you can just use the kitchen in the apartment to cook yourself a meal and enjoy a nice comfy stay. With an iconic skyline towering over London, striking and dynamic architecture and a vibrant, cosmopolitan feel, Canary Wharf is firmly established as a first class shopping and leisure destination There are plenty of bars, pubs, restaurants, luxury stores to shop and a massive shopping mall.  Canary Wharf is a major business district located in Tow

host_about:
My name is Fabio and I along with my friend and colleague Willian will ensure to provide you a wonderful stay in our apartments across London.

Willian, Throughout his extensive travels, his unusual name – a derivative of William – has led to much curiosity. An Ecuadorian by birth, He has added to my higher education internationally, with economic studies in the USA, language training in Japan, and a BA and MBA in the United Kingdom.

I am a 37 year old professional, currently working and living in London, Willian is 30 year old professional, currently working and living in lively London. the most exciting and bigger property market in the world. During all this description of myself well mostly Willian, you will find out how travelling could probably be Willian's and I number 1 hobbie. Although, We do not see it as a hobby but a luxury :). We do also enjoy playing sports, attending concerts, going to the movies, clubbing, hanging out, cooking and much more! 

Airbnb is awesome. Willian remembers his first time using the portal was back in 2010, when he travelled to Tokyo to attend an university interview over there. He had booked an comfortable duplex apartment in Shinjuku from this lovely Japanese guy, Junichi. He was amazed to see the true meaning of hospitality, being a host is more than just being the doorman or the typical receptionist at concierge, it is being someone who receives, treat and entertains other people as guests. 

All my life Willian and I have dedicated quite a lot of time to travel around the globe where We have had the opportunity to meet amazing people and experienced other cultures, costumes, and more. That is exactly why I am currently working in the hospitality industry with my colleague and friend Fabio because what I have learned all these years travelling around is that hospitality is the friendly and generous reception and entertainment of guests, visitors, or strangers not matter where people come from.

Fabio and I look forward welcoming and hosting some many guest in the upcoming years. I will truly give you my 100% to ensure your stay goes very well why you are staying at my apartments. I hope you enjoy the experience and adventure and thank you in advance :).

Your hosts,
Willian - Fabio

host_about:
Hi, I'm Richard. 25 years ago, I opened a very popular little Japanese restaurant in London's Chinatown called Tokyo Diner.  Although I no longer work on the Front Desk, I'm still the owner - so I interview all the staff (in Japanese) and I taste everything on the menu.

My flat is just the other side of Chinatown and I have a couple of extra bedrooms which are needed when chefs and other visitors come over from Japan. However, those rooms are empty for most of the time, so that's why I have decided to start using Airbnb.

My motto is "clean living, fun loving". I have always liked to exercise in the parks (just four minutes away) and, in the last couple of years, I have been completely taken over by Swing dancing (Lindyhop, Blues, Balboa). There is a real explosion of Swing in London at the moment and I usually go dancing five or six nights a week - so it's really convenient that I live in the centre of town!

We love walking the streets of this neighborhood, and we will gladly suggest fun walks depending on your interests. Stroll to the beach at Madison Park. Walk by multi-million dollar estates. host_about:
My name is Fabio and I along with my friend and colleague Willian will ensure to provide you a wonderful stay in our apartments across London.

Willian, Throughout his extensive travels, his unusual name – a derivative of William – has led to much curiosity. An Ecuadorian by birth, He has added to my higher education internationally, with economic studies in the USA, language training in Japan, and a BA and MBA in the United Kingdom.

I am a 37 year old professional, currently working and living in London, Willian is 30 year old professional, currently working and living in lively London. the most exciting and bigger property market in the world. During all this description of myself well mostly Willian, you will find out how travelling could probably be Willian's and I number 1 hobbie. Although, We do not see it as a hobby but a luxury :). We do also enjoy playing sports, attending concerts, going to the movies, clubbing, hanging out, cooking and much more! 

Airbnb is awesome. Willian remembers his first time using the portal was back in 2010, when he travelled to Tokyo to attend an university interview over there. He had booked an comfortable duplex apartment in Shinjuku from this lovely Japanese guy, Junichi. He was amazed to see the true meaning of hospitality, being a host is more than just being the doorman or the typical receptionist at concierge, it is being someone who receives, treat and entertains other people as guests. 

All my life Willian and I have dedicated quite a lot of time to travel around the globe where We have had the opportunity to meet amazing people and experienced other cultures, costumes, and more. That is exactly why I am currently working in the hospitality industry with my colleague and friend Fabio because what I have learned all these years travelling around is that hospitality is the friendly and generous reception and entertainment of guests, visitors, or strangers not matter where people come from.

Fabio and I look forward welcoming and hosting some many guest in the upcoming years. I will truly give you my 100% to ensure your stay goes very well why you are staying at my apartments. I hope you enjoy the experience and adventure and thank you in advance :).

Your hosts,
Willian - Fabio

host_about:
I keep a Busy schedule working as a mathematics high school teacher during the week and working as an entertainer DJ on the weekend. 

I enjoy Latin and top 40 music. During the spring and summer I go a few times SUPing (Stand up boarding) This is part of the Southern California life Style.

I have found that airbnb gives you a chance to interact with people more than a regular hotel stay. I prefer to meet people at hostels and BNB than a small hotel room where you don't get to interact with others as much.

I really love traveling. My job as a teacher has given me lost of vacation time. I have been to Buenos Aires, Iguazu Falls, The Amazon, Machu Pichu, Quito, Ecuador, Bogota, Cartagena, most of Colombia, Panama City, Managua and Leon in Nicaragua, Arenal Volcano and Jaco Beach in Costa Rica, Chichen Itza, Playa del Carmen, Cancun, Mexico City, Acapulco, Cabo San Lucas, most of western US. Niagara Falls, NYC, Virginia, Miami, Key West, Vancouver Canada, Dominican Republic, London, Amsterdam, Hamburg, Belgium, Paris, Nice, France, Hawaii, Tokyo, Kyoto, Hiroshima, Fukuoka.

I have been to Mexico city several times. Last time I took a bus from Mexico city to Acapulco. I really enjoyed that trip. Acapulco has the old and the new. Is pretty cool. Of course, you have to be careful around the city.

It is one of the United Kingdom's two main financial centres – along with the traditional City of London – and contains many of the UK's tallest buildings, including the second-tallest, One Canada Square.

host_about: Hi - I'm Jennifer. I'm originally from Charleston, S.C. and lived there until my early 20's. I graduated from the University of North Carolina - Charlotte in 1995 and received my B.A. in English Literature. I moved to Tokyo, Japan to teach English in 1998 and loved my two years there. I hope to move back there one day! In 2000, I moved to San Francisco. After being a resident here for almost 17 years, I still think it's the most beautiful city I've ever seen. I moved to Bernal Heights in 2011 and it's been my favorite neighborhood I've lived in in San Francisco. Bernal is more like a little village with amazing walk ability, shops, cafes and Bernal Mountain has some of the best views in the city.  I work in Sales and my hobbies are cooking, baking, hiking, camping, reading, playing tennis, dining out, traveling and spending time with my son, husband and Poodle-Mix, Sunny.  On my bucket list for places to visit are: Spain, Peru, Morocco, Cuba, Switzerland, Scotland, Vietman and Australia. Some of my favorite places I've traveled to are: Japan, Thailand, Italy, Ireland, Netherlands and New Zealand. My favorite books are: "East of Eden" and "Frankenstein" and my husband and I enjoy watching: Homeland, House of Cards, Orange is the New Black, Stranger Things and  American Crime. I love meeting people from all over the world and hope to meet you and host you soon!

neighborhood_overview: Clapham has two main areas for evening entertainment; Clapham High Street and Clapham Junction. Clapham Junction boasts the famous Clapham Grand, a venue hosting a great variety of events depending on the night. Most tastes are catered for in the Grand at some time or other, and the place has a great feel to it. Inigo is a much smaller bar/club about five minutes from the station, and plays a wide range of funky house and dance music along with regular promotional drinks offers. Clapham Junction also has a Rileys' 24-hour pool bar, which is a bit of a boys club and hosts both pool and poker tournaments.
transit: Transportation Clapham Junction is about eight minutes from Waterloo, with 35 trains an hour. It's nice to have guaranteed timing in your journey to work! There are no Underground stations in Clapham Junction but with so many trains, it hardly seems to matter. The station also provides you with the opportunity for a day out almost anywhere in the south of England without too much hassle. The High Street has three stations on the Northern Line (Clapham South, North and Common), which can all have you in the West End or the city in fifteen minutes . Clapham High Street, a small usually unmanned station, also has a service to Victoria. The area also has regular night buses from central London; so you'll never have to leave your drink/pull/friends to go and catch that irritatingly full last train home.

host_about:
My name is Fabio and I along with my friend and colleague Willian will ensure to provide you a wonderful stay in our apartments across London.

Willian, Throughout his extensive travels, his unusual name – a derivative of William – has led to much curiosity. An Ecuadorian by birth, He has added to my higher education internationally, with economic studies in the USA, language training in Japan, and a BA and MBA in the United Kingdom.

I am a 37 year old professional, currently working and living in London, Willian is 30 year old professional, currently working and living in lively London. the most exciting and bigger property market in the world. During all this description of myself well mostly Willian, you will find out how travelling could probably be Willian's and I number 1 hobbie. Although, We do not see it as a hobby but a luxury :). We do also enjoy playing sports, attending concerts, going to the movies, clubbing, hanging out, cooking and much more! 

Airbnb is awesome. Willian remembers his first time using the portal was back in 2010, when he travelled to Tokyo to attend an university interview over there. He had booked an comfortable duplex apartment in Shinjuku from this lovely Japanese guy, Junichi. He was amazed to see the true meaning of hospitality, being a host is more than just being the doorman or the typical receptionist at concierge, it is being someone who receives, treat and entertains other people as guests. 

All my life Willian and I have dedicated quite a lot of time to travel around the globe where We have had the opportunity to meet amazing people and experienced other cultures, costumes, and more. That is exactly why I am currently working in the hospitality industry with my colleague and friend Fabio because what I have learned all these years travelling around is that hospitality is the friendly and generous reception and entertainment of guests, visitors, or strangers not matter where people come from.

Fabio and I look forward welcoming and hosting some many guest in the upcoming years. I will truly give you my 100% to ensure your stay goes very well why you are staying at my apartments. I hope you enjoy the experience and adventure and thank you in advance :).

Your hosts,
Willian - Fabio

neighborhood_overview: I absolutely adore my neighborhood Treptow! It's super green, safe and quiet with the park and the small lake just across the street, you can walk to river Spree across the park.  At the same time, it"s really close to all the happening areas, Kreuzberg, Neukölln and Friedrichshain. If you don"t want to walk there or take a taxi, feel free to use my bicyles to get around!
notes: One important reminder at this point:  I am a dog lover and my adorable dog Luna lives me in my flat. I do not believe that dogs are in any way unhygienic, at least not more than humans.  It is unavoidable despite all efforts to clean and hover the flat that there will be places where you spot dog hair.  If that is something that bothers or concerns you, I recommend looking for alternative options.
transit: My place is conveniently located to public transport: closest S-bahn station is "Treptower Park" on the ring (circle) train  10min leisurely walk  through the park and bus stop just outside of the house.
access: I like my guests to feel at home away from home. With that, there are no limits to communal areas and rooms they can access or use, as long as they keep them clean and ready for use by others.  I appreciate if guests are not hiding in their room and keeping to themselves but I do encourage them to share the public spaces.  On the same note, I expect that guests do not regard their room as their private property and accept that I may have to access the room to get some things or use it while they are not using it themselves.  I am looking at this more than a shared flat with temporary guests than a hotel where people check in, do their thing and check out.  Of course, mutual respect and trust is the basis for this kind of openness which is both granted  by myself as well as expected from my guests.
interaction: The level of interaction with my guests generally depends on a range of different factors such as my guest's travel plans, my own work and social calendar how much interaction we will have. Generally speaking, I do find the social dimension of AirBnB at least equally attractive as the financial award as a host. Therefore, I do not like guests to treat me as an employee in a hotel that will do the check-in and check-out but would like to remind everyone that for whatever limited time we have, we are sharing together this space, with me included. Interaction and communication between us make these moments much more valuable and interesting for both myself and my guests.  I greatly enjoy sharing with my guests my story, my view of Berlin, favorite places, clubs, art venues, cafes, neighborhoods and the reasons why I love this city more than any other.   The fascinating thing for me is this: I always learn something new from my guests that I did not know, experienced or paid attention to!
house_rules: I kindly ask my guest to respect the following house rules:  1. Please remove your shoes when entering the flat, I am happy to provide some extra shoes for the house. That protects the antique wooden parquet floor and reduces the noise level for my downstairs neighbor.  2. Smoking is not permitted inside the flat, only on both balconies. 3. Please respect my neighbors and avoid excessive noise in the flat, particularly between 10pm and 8am. This also includes the staircase when you return late at night.  NOTE: my downstairs neighbor has his bedroom under my kitchen. Noise travels more easily in an old house like mine. I recommend using the living room when you want to sit together in the evening to have drinks.  4. Parties are explicitly NOT allowed, unless you have prior approval, particularly if it involves inviting non-guests to the flat.  5. Please keep the kitchen area clean and tidy, put away into the dishwasher or wash any dirty dishes. 6. One last important house rule for MALE
host_about:
Hi there, I am George and proud to be AirBnB Superhost for the 10th time in a row! I love hosting people from all over the world. 
What I enjoyed most during my 18-month travel around the world a few years ago was to spend time with friends who were kind enough to host me in their homes (San Francisco, Tokyo, Miami, Rio de Janeiro just to name a few). Now that I have settled down in my favorite city Berlin, I love to return the  favor and open up my place to guests from other countries and cultures to make it their home away from home.
I am a gay man, currently living by myself  with my adorable dog Luna, a German short hair pointer after my longtime Brazilian partner from Rio de Janeiro moved out to start a degree in 'Fashion Branding'  @ Amsterdam Fashion Institute (AmFI). I have always enjoyed hosting other people, showing them my city and sharing with them my view of Berlin, what to do and how to make the most of their time. 
Professionally, I work as an business consultant for a big American company. As a balance for my creative half I like art (both visiting exhibitions as well as getting my own small eclectic collection), going for long walks with my dog in the country side around Berlin, architecture, traveling, enjoying the amazing cultural offers in Berlin ranging from opera to nights (and days) in my favorite club Berghain. But above all, I am  a huge fan of Franco-Belgian comics such as Tintin, Blake & Mortimer, Sopie & Starter etc. Not only do I collect these comics but I also collect art work such as Aroutcheff toys, cars and vehicles. 
The other passion is decorating my apartement with rare antiques and art work. It makes me proud that virtually anyone who comes to visit immediately falls in love with my flat. 
My favorite author is Haruki Murakami, about time he gets the Nobel prize for literature! Favorite destinations are Nepal, Japan and Easter Islands. 
If I am not busy enjoying the cultural attractions of Berlin, I love watching well made US series e.g. Sopranos, The Wire and Game of Thrones. 
Favorite directors are Pedro Almodovar, David Lynch, Jim Jarmusch and Francois Truffeaut. 
If you stay with me, you should not be afraid of dogs. I would like my guests to really feel at home at my place and invite them to the  entire space rather than just their room for cooking, relaxing, borrowing my books or taking a sun bath on one of my balconies. 
My leitmotiv is "Work hard & party hard" and "Live and let live", I am tolerant towards other views and opinions as long as they do the same. I hate intolerant and hypocritical people who think they have eaten the truth with a spoon. Gay and lesbian friendly!

host_about:
I came to Sydney from Japan more than 10 years ago. I fell in love when I saw so many dolphins playing with surfers near Bondi Beach on one glorious Saturday morning, just 20min away from CBD Sydney. Coming from Tokyo, I never forget how surprised I was! I have been living in beautiful Sydney ever since. 

When I met Peter,  he was already living in The Rocks/Millers Point where it's 5min walk to Sydney Harbour Bridge, 15min walks to Sydney Opera House yet quiet, absolutely a hidden gem. We enjoyed living there for a while and ended up creating art gallery space home, hosting so many art exhibitions 2008-2013 and welcoming servas guests, house swaps and then airbnb guests all over the world.  

Then beautiful Sachi came into our life. 
A baby comes with changes, we have left beloved Millers Point and now living in Central Macdonald, 1,5hrs north west from Sydney where there are lots of cows and horses and the Hawksbury river just down the road. We purchased a little church on the hills there and dream to create a very special beautiful space where we can call it our home and also to host Airbnb guests. 

We embrace changes in life therefore love traveling, we have been to many places. 

Peter is a video producer, running his own company after working for SBS Television as a promo producer for more than a decade. He makes beautiful videography ((URL HIDDEN) and currently leading TEDxSydney video team. I am an art therapist. I enjoy magical moments with kids who have lots of stories to tell. 

Looking forward to meeting you:):):)
